'''Stephen John Fry''' (b. [[24 August|August 24]], [[1957]]) is an English actor, screenwriter, author, playwright, journalist, poet, comedian, television presenter and film director. He portrayed the [[Master of Lake-town]] in [[The Hobbit (film series)|''The Hobbit'' (film series)]].

==Quotes==
{{quote|Remember the question before the time and they are a threat to [[Smaug]].|Stephen Fry, YouTube}}
{{quote|I suppose the real biggie is free will. I find it interesting that no one really talks about it: I would say that 98 per cent of all philosophers would agree with me that essentially free will is a myth. It doesn’t exist. That ought to be shocking news on the front of every newspaper. I’m not saying we don’t look both ways before we cross the road; we decide not to leave it to luck as to whether a car is going to hit us. Nor am I saying that we don’t have responsibility for our actions: we have agency over the body in which our minds and consciousness dwell. But we can’t choose our brains, we can’t choose our genes, we can’t choose our parents.|Stephen Fry, The Sydney Morning Herald}}
{{Quote|I’m savvy. Somebody has to take over the mantle from [[Orlando Bloom]], as the most desirable figure to be in [[Portal:Adaptations|a Tolkien adaptation]]|Stephen Fry, The Hobbit: The Desolation of Smaug: Live Event: In The Cutting Room}}
{{Quote|I’m a extremely greedy [[Master of Lake-town|character,]] corrupt character, and its perhaps the only moment in wherein ''[[The Hobbit]]'' [[J.R.R. Tolkien|Tolkien]] gets into a bit of politics, satire on, you know, local government.|Stephen Fry, The Hobbit: The Desolation of Smaug: Live Event: In The Cutting Room}}

